Statement of the Witness/Accused. I stared at the heading of the form given to me by the police officer with dread. Whatever I wrote there would either send some innocents to jail or wreck a marriage. My neighbour, Shade looked at me with an inscrutable expression on her face. She could save the situation by explaining who was at her flat and at what time, but that as we well knew would lead to more questions and eventually to the Landlord’s wife. Then it will be the Landlord that would need to make an accused statement to his wife.

&nbsp;

They seemed so close. My Landlord and his wife. Even my wife said so, as they ‘interviewed’ us four years ago to see if we merited the position of being their tenants. We passed by virtue of my job with an oil company but most importantly, because my wife was from Ondo State. It was not an issue of tribalism, as Mr and Mrs Landlord as we called them, though <em>Yoruba </em>in origin, were not from Ondo. It was because they believed that women from certain parts of Nigerian, Ondo included, were good housekeepers. That was the level of interest they took in their tenants, insisting that they interviewed each one. Before long, a pattern had emerged. Mr and Mrs Landlord would only let their flats to married couples, with the wife being of high educational background (she was not likely to ‘breed’ children’), good jobs and well brought up children. All other persons, no matter how well endowed, would not pass the Landlords test.

I must admit that though I found their system parochial, it seemed to work. All tenants got on well together, contributing when required to the general upkeep of the building and there was little or no friction in the house with all of us keeping to ourselves.

&nbsp;

Then the first issue occurred. One of the neighbours raised an alarm that she had lost a significant amount of jewellery. After questioning by her own husband, she admitted that she might have lent it to a friend, as she was wont to do. We left her to crack her brain on which friend or acquaintance would have the pieces of jewellery. The second issue was the appearance of ‘Mrs’ Shade Balogun. I have queried the use of ‘Mrs’ as we never saw her with any husband. It seemed quite odd that she had been able to pass the Mr and Mrs Landlord test. The third issue was when one of the tenants lost his elder brother and was compelled to look after his brother’s son.

&nbsp;

From day 1, Emeka, the bereaved son was a handful.  There were rows from the flat, he stole his uncle’s car to go all night partying, the diesel from the generator got missing, he fought with the security guard, the list was endless. <u>“What has Emeka done now?” was a common refrain in the compound.</u> When the Landlord raised the issue with me, I pleaded for his understanding as the young lad had just lost his father and was bound to react, one way or another.

&nbsp;

<span style="color: #ff6600;"><a style="color: #ff6600;" href="https://castles.com.ng/my-landlord-has-cheated-me-2/"><strong>Related Article: My Landlord has cheated me!</strong></a></span>

&nbsp;

Life continued as usual, until one fateful Friday night, or should I say morning. I had been tossing and turning all night, feeling very restless and in order not to disturb my wife, got up from bed and sat on a chair on my veranda, enjoying the early morning breeze. I knew it was 2 a.m. in the morning because I had glanced casually at the clock in the living room. As I sat blowing to cool a cup of tea I had made, I saw a movement. Emeka had left the confines of his uncle’s flat, crept to the low end of the fence and jumped out. I had hardly started shaking my head in disgust when I noticed another sound. Someone had left Mrs Balogun’s flat and was also creeping out of the compound. As the person passed the security light, his face was clearly visible, even in the dark. It was Mr Landlord. Belying his age, he nimbly climbed over the fence and was off. A minute later, I heard the sound of a car. The sound must have woken up our lazy guard who walked out of his shed, looked up, saw me and waved “ I no dey sleep” he called in pidgin English.

&nbsp;

Later that morning was the uproar. Someone had stolen one of the co-tenant’s jewellery. It was an inside job and so all suspicion immediately went to Emeka. As he was not back from his sojourn, it was assumed that he had escaped. I contributed the information that I had seen him climbing the gate at 2 o’clock in the morning. Then the rascal walked in, cool as a cucumber. If he indeed stole the jewellery,  the boy was a first class actor. He denied it completely. My irate neighbours took the matter to the police, where I was a prime witness. Emeka insisted that not only had he not taken the jewellery, there was a man who jumped the fence after him. He did not recognise the person but if I had seen him, Emeka, climb the fence, I must have seen the other person. Emeka, as well as all the other tenants and the policemen, turned their gaze at me. At that moment, Mr and Mrs Landlord walked into the station. I saw Emeka’s looking them but obviously he did not recognise the landlord as the man who climbed the gate. Everyone’s attention turned back to me: was it true that I saw someone else climb out over the fence?

&nbsp;

<strong><em>How should I answer? If I tell the truth, then the landlord will have to answer to his wife. Or he may deny it and then it would be his word against mine. Either way, they will not be favourable when I come to renew my rent, that is, if they renew it at all. On the other hand, if I do not, then Emeka ‘s guilt, which I am not sure of, will be confirmed. Help! I need advice. email: feedback@castles.com.ng</em></strong>

&nbsp;

In the history of briefings and meetings between clients and their architects, these words have probably never been uttered. But as we will see from the following pages, the size, orientation, angling and materials of the windows has not only a dramatic effect on the façade of the building but is also relevant for energy efficiency.

&nbsp;

<strong><img class="alignnone  wp-image-62537" src="https://castles.com.ng/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/Fenestration-4-300x61.jpg" alt="" width="634" height="129" /></strong>

&nbsp;

<strong>Fenestration</strong> (architecture), refers to the design, construction, or presence of openings in a building. <strong>Fenestration</strong> includes windows, doors, louvres, vents, wall panels, skylights, storefronts, curtain walls, and slope glazed systems.

&nbsp;

<img class="alignnone  wp-image-62540" src="https://castles.com.ng/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/Fenestration-300x220.jpg" alt="" width="466" height="342" />

<span style="color: #ff6600;"><a style="color: #ff6600;" href="https://castles.com.ng/exceptional-showerheads/"><strong>Related Article: Exceptional showerheads</strong></a></span>

[caption id="attachment_62541" align="alignnone" width="489"]<img class=" wp-image-62541" src="https://castles.com.ng/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/Fenestration-2-300x248.jpg" alt="" width="489" height="404" /> This façade of the rear of this terrace of 4 houses projected for Abuja Nigeria was rescued from blandness. According to Chuka, “ there was a clear intention to produce an entry facade with identical but distinctive entrances. The red portals achieve this”. Apart from their aesthetic appeal, each portal acts as a canopy for the doorway as well as the final step up to the unit.[/caption]

&nbsp;

[caption id="attachment_62542" align="alignnone" width="486"]<img class=" wp-image-62542" src="https://castles.com.ng/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/Fenestration-3-297x300.jpg" alt="" width="486" height="491" /> A cantilever roof terrace cover with oculus is the immediate focal point of this design. But by restraining himself from slapping regular large windows on the ‘non-communicating’ street view, the façade has a more intriguing presence. If windows are the ‘eyes’ of a building, one gets the impression of the left eye shut and the right one squinting to focus on an object.[/caption]

The popular traditional model for delivering small building projects where the project owner engages a supervising engineer, builder or contractor and handles the procurement of the materials for the job themselves is now creeply deeply into bigger projects. At least half the projects currently embarked upon by private developers across the country are delivered using this model. The reason for this trend are largely blamed on the overbearing activities of unscrupulous contractors who have made cutting corners a way of life; thereby creating a lot of distrust in the larger circle. Although this model is now largely adopted as a soft landing approach for project owners over the full contract option, if not checked properly, the real objective will be defeated.

&nbsp;

Here are the issues; first you have to engage a competent hand as your supervisor - one who knows the job and is honesty and discipline - very important. Here is why – project happens when materials meet workmanship and supervision in the presence of a catalyst called money. They don’t just happen! Of these three items, the cost associated with materials normally account for some 60 percent of the entire project cost. Therefore naturally, procurement becomes the ‘big fish’.

&nbsp;

Now it feels smart for a project owner to take on procurement at least to save overall cost and no one will have to accuse you of suffering from acute owner-contractor syndrome (OCS) since you have already engaged a professional on site responsible for managing the construction aspect of the project. Moreso since not much technical skills is needed in mobilizing materials to site. But there is a negative trend now that you may not know.

<span style="color: #ff6600;"><a style="color: #ff6600;" href="https://castles.com.ng/eoi-construction-of-obudu-cargo-international-airport/"><strong>Related Article: Construction of Obudu Cargo/International Airport</strong></a></span>

Unscrupulous Supervising engineers/Contractors connive with suppliers to manipulate quantities and quality of materials delivered to site in order to get huge cuts in return and this runs throughout the project life cycle. In the process, the owner loses some good amount of project funds. For instance in the first quarter of 2019 alone, a well-known construction supply merchant in Nigeria – SupplyQuickNG recorded at least 16 cases of Site supervisors demanding that they either deliver materials of lesser qualities or quantities than what was requested by their Client or risk losing the supply deal and that the balance from such malicious transactions be paid directly to them. The business manager of the company further revealed that some 77 million naira combined would have been lost by the unsuspecting client in those deals if the company had danced to the tune been played. On one occasion, she recalled that a client ordered for 31 tons of reinforcement based on the bill of quantities he received from his contractor but at the point of loading at the stores, the resident engineer called in to demand that only 22-tons be delivered; that he deliberately scaled up the quantities to 31 so that upon payment, the money for 9 tons can be recalled and paid directly to him. That would have been about 2 million naira loss for the client at an instance if they had compromised.

&nbsp;

Another disturbing trend observed is that some will ask that the supplier manipulates the quality of the materials by delivering a mix of substandard and good quality products which is against the original order made by the Client and since they are to approve the delivery, they would simply turn a blind eye to it. Again the idea is to profit illegally at the expense of the integrity of the structure and the trust repose on them by the unsuspecting client. When suppliers refuse to engage in such double-dealings, they lay trumped-up allegations against the supplier to compel the client to reject the delivery. This is just a few of the many issues bordering on the adoption of this model for construction projects, although it has its own merits.

&nbsp;

In order to curb these excesses, some developers have had to set up a procurement office within the site management structure which will be responsibility for ensuring that only the right qualities and quantities of materials required are delivered to site. Such formation would normally consist of a Quality Control experts and QS. The deployment of technology in procurement processes which allows for minimal exposure to site personnel will also do a great deal.

&nbsp;

[caption id="attachment_63885" align="alignnone" width="354"]<img class=" wp-image-63885" src="https://castles.com.ng/wp-content/uploads/2019/05/ENg.jpg" alt="" width="354" height="271" /> Engr. Osaz’ ENOBAKHARE is CEO of Heavens Contractors Ltd<br />(HEAVENSCON)<br />Phone: 08167394799<br />Mail: osaz@heavenscontractors.com<br />Twitter: @engineerosaz<br />Blog: www.engineerosaz.blogpot.com[/caption]

Real estate is a capital good and typically requires a large investment sum. The returns are very good, often better than most other investment classes and serves as a hedge against inflation in the long run. However, this investment sum is often hard to come by for the average individual and so it’s important to think critically about how to get in on real estate investments. Here we share three tips to investing in real estate without necessarily breaking the bank.

&nbsp;

In this article we are not going to share anything that’s not in the open, it’s definitely not illegal and the ideas are common knowledge. But what may be new is your perspective to real estate investment. People typically think until you own a property that you can visit you have not invested in real estate. Some tips here will not work for you if you still hold that view. Same way as you buy Dangote shares but cannot even visit a Dangote cement plant without a proper invitation or agenda, real estate investment is primarily for the returns you get and not the “feeling” of ownership.

<span style="color: #ff6600;"><a style="color: #ff6600;" href="https://castles.com.ng/exceptional-real-estate-opportunities-in-the-lekki-axis/"><strong>Related Article: Exceptional Real Estate Opportunities in the Lekki Axis</strong></a></span>

With that out of the way, the first way you can invest in real estate with significantly less than a million is by buying the shares of real estate companies. This is a type of “indirect real estate”. Real estate companies typically invest in real estate, so when you buy their shares you are indirectly investing in real estate. Similarly, you can invest in REITs – Real Estate Investment Trusts. They are vehicles that invest primarily in real estate and have a statutory obligation to distribute at least 90% of their annual profit. This makes REITs even more liquid as an investment than most real estate company shares. There are very few real estate shares and REITs in Nigeria but they exist and provide a good platform for you to start your real estate investment journey.

&nbsp;

Secondly, you may invest in real estate by pooling funds together with others. This may be through investment clubs, cooperatives or adapting technology through crowdfunding and co-investing platforms like Cobuildit and Coreum. The age old adage – “There is power in numbers” is the rule here and it works. Your one million Naira may not be able to buy more than 10 square metres of land in Lekki but when one hundred people come together, each with a million, they may be able to buy a full plot. Maybe not up to a standard plot, but you get the message. What is essential is everyone gets the same percentage return proportionate to the size of her/his investment.

&nbsp;

Finally, you may invest in property itself. However, due to the low investment sum you have, you have to be very creative. You actually have to be super creative. If you want to invest directly in real estate with less than one million, you will need to do a lot of research and bet on a location that is not yet developed but you believe will be developed soon. The reality is, most places on earth will be developed in one form or another at some point, the million Naira question is how long will it take? These are decisions a good broker can help you discern but the final decision on which option to take will be up to you.

&nbsp;

[caption id="attachment_63898" align="alignnone" width="257"]<img class=" wp-image-63898" src="https://castles.com.ng/wp-content/uploads/2019/05/3-ways-to-invest-in-real-estate-with-less-than-a-million-1.jpg" alt="" width="257" height="171" /> Tayo Odunsi CEO, Northcourt RealEstate<br />Tayo.odunsi@northcourtrealestate.com[/caption]

&nbsp;

[caption id="attachment_63900" align="alignnone" width="159"]<img class=" wp-image-63900" src="https://castles.com.ng/wp-content/uploads/2019/05/3-ways-to-invest-in-real-estate-with-less-than-a-million-2.jpg" alt="" width="159" height="233" /> Niyi Olumoto, Brokerage Lead, Northcourt RealEstate<br />Niyi.olumoto@northcourtrealestate.com[/caption]

Whether you’re an investor or seeking to buy a property to occupy, most people are often lost on what exactly to buy, when they want to buy. Asides from being spoilt for choice in today’s market, you need to decide on what type of property, location, grade, style, age, off-plan or not, use-type and most importantly, ensuring you get it at the right price. If you’re still reading you probably are in this category and we have three easy questions you need to ask yourself. Interpretations of your answers to these questions will help lead you quickly to what you should buy. This is kind of how a doctor asks you a few random questions and then diagnoses your ailment, or simply says you need to rest more.

&nbsp;

Anyways, first, ask yourself; “what’s my risk appetite?”. You may not be an investment guru, but it’s important to understand that any form of investment or even large purchase such as a personal home has some risk, and there are many types. Two critical risks in investing in property include market risk and liquidity risk. Market risk refers to you being exposed to the performance of your property due to economic factors while liquidity risk infers you the ability of the property to be easily sold to get cash when you need it. The property, in general, is quite illiquid, relative to several other investments (stocks and bonds), but some properties are more illiquid than others. So it’s key to ask yourself, “how much market or liquidity risk am I willing to take?”.

<a href="https://castles.com.ng/3-ways-to-invest-in-real-estate-with-less-than-a-million/"><strong>Read Also: 3 Ways to Invest in Real Estate with Less than a Million</strong></a>

If you’re buying off-plan or building yourself, you are exposed to the construction risk or performance risk of the developer or contractor respectively. This is the risk of you investing your funds and the other party not delivering either fully or partially. A lot of people think building themselves guarantees all things, but they are merely opening themselves up to this new risk (construction risk). It often goes south, but it often doesn’t too, if you carefully mitigate this risk by selecting your developer or contractor with insight.

&nbsp;

The second question to ask yourself is “what type of return do I want?”. Often people think of real estate as just houses. That’s just one sub-sector (residential). There are several others and each sub-sector typically give different levels of return. In classic textbook fashion, the major types of real estate in ascending order of return (profitability) are agricultural real estate, residential, office, retail, logistics, and hospitality. Again, it does not always work out this way, as some particular properties may outperform their peers, so understand these classifications only as a general rule.

&nbsp;

The third question to ask yourself is “what is my preference?” or “what suits me?”. With the two questions above carefully considered, what’s next is to consider what works for you. The age-old adage – different strokes for different folks holds true. For example, due to how much you have, you may only be able to invest in a small retail shop, despite that you would like to buy a personal home in the near future. Or, if you want to tie investments to your children’s future education, you may want to invest in an apartment for each child as against hospitality or logistics which may be less clear cut and liquid. What is essential is to clarify your investment motives and goals, and then choose the best course that suits you in line with your risk and return appetite.

&nbsp;

[caption id="attachment_63898" align="alignnone" width="257"]<img class=" wp-image-63898" src="https://castles.com.ng/wp-content/uploads/2019/05/3-ways-to-invest-in-real-estate-with-less-than-a-million-1.jpg" alt="" width="257" height="171" /> Tayo Odunsi CEO, Northcourt RealEstate<br />Tayo.odunsi@northcourtrealestate.com[/caption]

&nbsp;

[caption id="attachment_63900" align="alignnone" width="159"]<img class=" wp-image-63900" src="https://castles.com.ng/wp-content/uploads/2019/05/3-ways-to-invest-in-real-estate-with-less-than-a-million-2.jpg" alt="" width="159" height="233" /> Niyi Olumoto, Brokerage Lead, Northcourt RealEstate<br />Niyi.olumoto@northcourtrealestate.com[/caption]

If we received just one hundred Naira for each time a client asked “Which is better and cheaper – should I buy or build a house?”, we would have earned well over a million Naira. Thinking of it, this question is actually worth millions. But on the surface, it should be cheaper to build a house as against buying. This is because the alternative to the building would be to buy from a developer or reseller, who would have included a profit margin, thereby making it more expensive than the cost of the building. But this is often not the case, in fact, it seldom is. In this article, we will share a few reasons why it may be better to buy a house than to build and also share the scenarios where it is better to build over buying. While this information may help you assess your situation and determine which category you find yourself, it is advisable that you engage a professional real estate advisor to conduct a “make or buy analysis” on your behalf if you’re in this particular bind.

<a href="https://castles.com.ng/what-to-buy-when-you-dont-know-what-to-buy/"><strong>Read Also: What to Buy When you Don't Know What to Buy</strong></a>

One primary scenario where buying may be better and cheaper than the building is in the case where you lack construction expertise. Constructing a property is a multifaceted endeavor requiring a myriad of skills ranging from design, quantities costing, building to construction project management. Should you lack these skills, you may over-pay, demand or procure low quality or unduly prolong the project. You may also have to arm yourself with one too many consultants which are likely to increase the project costs because you don’t have any technical skills.

&nbsp;

In many cases, multi-unit or multi-project developers and builders enjoy economies of scale which pushes their costs and turn around time down. This way, their per unit cost is often lower than when a user wants to build one or few of the same property type.

&nbsp;

Another reason it may be better to buy is when there is panic selling or a recessionary economy. In downturns, inflation is high so the cost of building materials go up, however people are in need of cash and willing to sell lower so property prices come down. This leaves a mismatch between built property prices and the cost of building new ones. It becomes significantly cheaper to buy an existing property than to build a new one. This is also the case when a property is on the market on a forced sale from a bank or financier. The property is often sold lower than its replacement cost.

&nbsp;

However, it becomes cheaper and better to build over buying when the property in question is to be specialized property. Developers often only have standard properties for sale. If a major specialty is required in a property, it is cheaper and faster to build over buying and then remodeling. Remodeling costs can quickly spiral out of control especially when structural alterations need to be done.

&nbsp;

Also, it is most likely cheaper for a construction savvy user to build over buying. His expertise not only reduces wastage, but it is also a cost input that s/he does not have to pay for in cash. It works out as sweat equity.

&nbsp;

Finally, it becomes better and cheaper to build in a booming or bullish economy. In such an economy property prices are on the rise and expectedly more profitable, allowing for any wastage even a first-time self-builder may incur. The building is also more desirable over buying when the entire construction sum is not available and the project will be executed in piecemeal. Piecemeal projects tend to be longer and more expensive, however, they have a significant and unassailable advantage, in that it reduces the entry barrier to property ownership.

